<Author>Belfast_traveller_8
<Content>Would not stay here again On the plus side, the room we were in had a lovely view of the hills southwest of Florence. The distance from the city centre was not too bad, i.e. about a 20-30 minute walk. However, there is very little within the immediate environs of the hotel - you have to walk for at least 10-15 minutes to come across any bars or restaurants. While we found this ok when the weather was good, on one day of our stay there was torrential rain and we (and all the other guests) were basically stuck in the 'hotel' for the evening, which was not pleasant.I say ' hotel' because Villa Carlotta should really be designated a BB - the star rating attached to it is misleading. We stayed here as part of a trip across Italy taking in a 3 star hotel in Venice, a 4 star in Verona, the Carlotta in Florence, and a 5 star in Rome: the Carlotta was by some distance the worst accommodation we stayed in. The picture of the front of the hotel was slightly misleading, as the outside terrace was never in use during our stay, even though it would have been pleasant to sit out.The rooms felt in need of refurbishment - the bathroom was tatty and dusty, and the wardrobe door in the bedroom did not shut - it sat permanently 2 inches ajar. More importantly, the curtains and shutters in the bedroom did not close - we had only a net curtain to keep out the lights from the street outside, so we didn't sleep well.There was no fire exit information in our room, and the internal fire doors in the hotel seemed to be permanently propped open (though to be fair, the 5 star we stayed at in Rome did the same thing).Our room was next to the 'office', i.e. the cupboard where all the cleaning materials were stored, and on more than one occasion we came out of our room and had to step over piles of dirty laundry from other rooms, which had been left all over the floor.The breakfast consisted of the cheapest, nastiest ingredients: cardboard-y croissants and bread, coffee that was undrinkable. Each time we asked for tea 'con latte' (with milk), it was brought without (again, this is fairly common in Italy, but at the other places we stayed, if we specifically requested milk, they did bring it).The TV channels were limited - we were looking forward to watching the Olympics during our travels, and every other hotel had Eurosport in English. The Villa Carlotta only had a German version available.Some of these complaints were really only minor irritations and could have been easily overcome by pleasant, friendly, welcoming staff. Unfortunately all of the staff we came across in our 3-day stay had very little to say to us beyond 'buon giorno' and 'buona sera'. Even when we came in after being caught in the torrential rain - literally soaked to the skin and dripping all over the carpet - the receptionist just smiled and said 'buona sera' and handed us our room key. The hotel didn't do room service but - as we were visibly soaked - I had been hoping they could send some hot tea up to our room. No. We had to get dried off, changed, and come down and get it from the bar.If the Carlotta had been a lot cheaper, it perhaps could have been good value, but for 130 euro a night it was a shameless rip-off. I would never stay here again and I certainly wouldn't recommend it to anyone. We couldn't wait to leave. 
