<Author>Socca
<Content>Comfort by the Romano Gates I reserved a room at the Hotel Villa Carlotta without checking this website first. Once I had seen the various reviews posted, I regretted my reservation. Yet, having prepaid my first night, I really had no good alternative but to check in. I visited the Hotel Villa Carlota during the period between Christmas 2006 and 1 January 2007 with my wife, soon to be 9-year-old daughter, and her little dog. We found it to be the kind of hotel that is most to our liking: not too large, service which is personal and personable but not intrusive, placed in, indeed part of an absolutely charming setting, in situ parking, a reasonably good dining room restaurant with fine Chianti Classico wines, and we were very happy with the arranged price. Our room was a good 20 square meters in size, comfortable, and reasonably furnished. The Breugel and Vincenzo on the wall were of the sort to really trouble Walter Benjamin, but even the David on display in the Piazza della Signora near the Uffizi is a copy. Florence itself is not far from becoming a kind of Disneyland of the Renaissance.The breakfast offered by the Villa Carlotta was quite fine and the breakfast area was pleasant. The famous annex seemed relatively unoccupied during our stay. The Ponte Vecchio is some 20 minutes away by foot, but it can be attained via a very pleasant walk through the Boboli Gardens. The Villa Carlotta is one of those nearly private European hotels where the murmur of various languages mixing over the aroma of good food reminds us of some of the best aspects of the past and encourages us to believe in a promising, prosperous, and peaceful European future. Who could ask for more? 
